HEADLINE: Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell on June 25, 2025, in Washington, DC
SOURCE: CNN (Opinion)

Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell on June 25, 2025, in Washington, DC. Kent Nishimura/Getty Images Donald Trump Federal agencies Interest rates Investing See all topics Facebook Tweet Email Link Link Copied! Follow Washington — The gloves are off in the heated clash between Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell and President Donald Trump. As extraordinary as a criminal investigation of a sitting Fed chair is, Powellâs rebuke of Trump was in some ways even more shocking. For years, Powell has remained mum even as Trump called him every name and used every insult in the book, repeatedly threatening to fire him. Powellâs playbook has been to remain neutral, saying his one and only focus was on the Fedâs politically independent mission to maintain maximum employment and low inflation. Everything else was a distraction, Powell maintained. Trump forced Powellâs hand after the Justice Department served him with subpoenas. But in Powellâs remarkable show of defiance, he didnât focus on his own actions but on defending the Fed against the Trump administrationâs attack on its independence â and, more broadly, the US economy. In his stunning two-minute video Sunday night, Powell characterized the Trump administrationâs potential prosecution as a threat against the livelihoods of the American public to serve Trumpâs whims. ï"¿âThe threat of criminal charges is a consequence of the Federal Reserve setting interest rates based on our best assessment of what will serve the public, rather than following the preferences of the president,â Powell said. âThis is about whether the Fed will be able to continue to set interest rates based on evidence and economic conditions â or whether instead monetary policy will be directed by political pressure or intimidation.â The fact that Powell spoke out forcefully against the Trump administration this week for the first time is all the more notable because Powell has long treasured and promoted the Fedâs independence, which he sees as tantamount to its mission to help American households live better lives. It enables the Fed to do its core mission: making jobs plentiful and keeping prices in check, even when politically imprudent. An emboldened Powell Economists, academics and former Fed officials broadly agree that safeguarding Fed independence is necessary for the soundness of the US economy. It ensures policymakers can make tough decisions on interest rates that are rooted in economic reality and not the whims of whoever controls the White House. For example, a president may want lower rates to grow the economy and send stocks higher, but that policy could hurt Americans by sending prices out of control. Powell has been an ardent defender of the Fedâs ability to set interest rates free of politics throughout Trumpâs relentless pressure campaign over the past year. For example, during a press conference in July, Powell was asked about Trumpâs recent attacks on him and the Fed. Powell didnât engage â but offered a long defense of the Fedâs independence. âIâll just say that, so I think that having an independent central bank has been an institutional arrangement that has served the public well. And as long as it serves the public well, it should continue and be respected. If it didnât serve the public well, then it wouldnât be something that we should just automatically defend,â Powell said. âBut what it gives us and other central banks, what it gives you is the ability to make these very challenging decisions that in ways that are focused on the data and the evolving outlook, the balance of risks and all of things we talk about, and not political factors.â Trump noted that the Fed is hardly alone â governments of advanced economies across the world have put distance between monetary policymakers and politicians. âIf you were not to have that, that would be a great temptation, of course, to use interest rates to affect elections, for example,â Powell added. âAnd thatâs something that we donât want to do.â An exterior view of the Marriner S. Eccles Federal Reserve building on November 29, 2025, in Washington, DC. Aaron M. Sprecher/AP Previously, the closest Powell had come to criticizing Trump was in November 2024, when he was asked whether he would leave his post early if Trump demanded it. âNo,â Powell said in a press conference. Asked to elaborate, Powell said, âNot permitted under the law.â Why the about face? Because Powell viewed the potential prosecution as an existential threat that could forever politicize the Fed, undermine its credibility and upset global markets and the economy. Thatâs part of the reason central bankers from around the world rallied to Powellâs defense Tuesday. In the statement, the worldâs central bankers stressed that the independence of central banks is a âcornerstone of price, financial and economic stabilityâ and that protecting that independence with full respect for the law is critical. The statement praised Powell for serving with âintegrityâ and for his âunwavering commitment to the public interest.â Fed remains independent, for now Among the many problems with Trumpâs demands for the Fed to lower rates is the perception of political interference when the Fed does take that action. The Fed in the second half of last year lowered interest rates three times in a row, though Trump has asked for more. Trump has said the United States should have rates that are among the lowest in the world and that he should have a say in rate decisions. To avoid the perception of influence, some Fed observers believe the central bank could hold off on rate cuts for longer. In other words, ridding the Fed of its independence could backfire spectacularly on Trump by making further rate cuts less likely and even emboldening Powell to remain on the Fedâs board after his term as chair ends on May 15. He is serving a concurrent term on the board that runs